{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"body":"[PASS 1 review — T3 Integration feasibility (epic-level, parent plan \"Repo-snapshot isolation for code-reading gates\")]\n\nAFFIRMATIONS (T3 criteria this plan satisfies):\n- technical_feasibility / named-subcommand existence — MATCH for the core git plumbing. The materialization primitive's chosen commands (`git fetch origin`, `git rev-parse`/ref→immutable-SHA resolution, `git read-tree <sha>` into a temp index via `GIT_INDEX_FILE`, `git checkout-index --all --prefix=<tmp>/`) are all real git subcommands, and git-as-subprocess is an ALREADY-USED integration in this repo (verified: src/rebar/_commands/{compact,delete,fsck,fsck_recover,txn,init,purge_bridge}.py and src/rebar/llm/plan_review/sidecar.py all shell `[\"git\", ...]`; signing.py head_sha() uses `git rev-parse`). Extending that established subprocess seam is not a new external-capability class — the base integration is NOT-APPLICABLE / PASS.\n- The attested-signing manifest channel (S4) is an INTERNAL already-used integration extended additively (signing._canonical_payload signs {v,algorithm,ticket_id,manifest}; the manifest step rides existing signed bytes with no PAYLOAD_VERSION bump) — T3 not-applicable / PASS for the signing channel.\n- auth/HTTPS preconditions stated — PASS. The plan/children pre-empt the arbitrary-SHA fetch precondition (`uploadpack.allowReachableSHA1InWant` or fetch-a-containing-ref-then-resolve; `--filter=blob:none`) and route private-repo credential failure to a descriptive, actionable error (S1 AC5, parent AC5).\n- SPIKE posture — PASS. The de-risking order front-loads the lock-free `read-tree`+`checkout-index` primitive as a thin vertical slice that proves the capability before the horizontal sweep, which functions as the spike T3 asks for. The rejected alternative (`git archive`) is named.\n- portability primitives — PASS. `fcntl.flock` + atomic-`mkdir` fallback and `tempfile.gettempdir()`/`mkdtemp` are stdlib; no external `tar` (parent AC6).\n\nFINDING:\n\n- [ ] Name the concrete git mechanism by which `read-tree`+`checkout-index` reproduces (or intentionally diverges from) the `export-ignore` / `export-subst` / submodule / LFS-pointer semantics, or route those sub-capabilities to a SPIKE — the plan asserts a \"faithful\" snapshot and the children assert \"LFS pointer files are detected\" + \"submodule handling is defined\" (S1 6d56 AC2) as OUTCOMES without naming HOW, and `read-tree`/`checkout-index` are not yet used anywhere in this repo (verified: zero matches for `read-tree`/`checkout-index`), so this is the one materialization sub-capability whose feasibility is asserted-but-unverified.\n  - criteria: T3 technical_feasibility; T3 named-subcommand existence = UNVERIFIED for the faithfulness sub-clauses.\n  - location: parent \"What\" (attested: \"faithful lock-free materialization into a content-addressed snapshot\") + parent AC1 (\"a faithful snapshot materialized at the pinned SHA\"); S1 6d56 \"What\" (FAITHFUL tree materialization bullet) + S1 6d56 AC1/AC2.\n  - evidence:\n    1. The EXISTING snapshot path documents archive-NATIVE behaviors that `checkout-index` does NOT replicate: src/rebar/llm/workflow/snapshot.py:23-27 — \"`git archive` ... `export-ignore` paths are omitted and `export-subst` is applied (git archive does this natively); **submodule** contents are NOT included (archive stops at the gitlink); **Git-LFS** files appear as their pointer text\". `export-ignore`/`export-subst` are git-ARCHIVE attributes; `git read-tree`+`git checkout-index` honor NEITHER and materialize the committed blob content as-is.\n    2. For an LFS-tracked path the committed blob content IS the ~130-byte `version https://git-lfs…` pointer; for a submodule the tree entry is a gitlink (mode 160000) that `checkout-index` does not populate. So S1 6d56 AC2's \"LFS pointer files are detected (not silently served as content)\" and \"submodule handling is defined\" are precisely the cases the chosen primitive does NOT resolve on its own — the plan asserts the outcome without a named command.\n    3. `read-tree`/`checkout-index` are NEW to this repo (search: zero matches), unlike the already-used `git archive`/`rev-parse`/`fetch` seam — so the faithfulness contract rides on a primitive that has not been exercised here.\n  - suggested_fix: In the parent \"What\" (and S1 6d56's \"What\"/AC2) name the LFS-detection mechanism (e.g. `.gitattributes` `filter=lfs` and/or the LFS pointer-file magic header; document whether real LFS content is fetched or the pointer is surfaced as a known limitation) and the submodule mechanism (e.g. `git ls-tree` gitlink enumeration; document recurse-vs-omit), AND state explicitly whether `read-tree`+`checkout-index` reproduces or intentionally diverges from `git archive`'s `export-ignore`/`export-subst` semantics documented in snapshot.py:23-27 (if it diverges, name the fidelity contract the gates rely on). Alternatively split LFS/submodule/export-attr faithfulness into a short SPIKE child, since it is the one materialization sub-capability not yet pinned to a named, repo-exercised command.\n\nNOTE (not a finding): the GitHub tarball API cited in the parent Context as a design influence is explicitly Out of scope (\"Sparse archiving\"; the materialize path is git-plumbing-only, no HTTPS tarball fetch). No child calls that API, so there is no asserted-but-unverified external endpoint — T3 not-applicable to the tarball reference; recorded so a later pass does not re-raise it as a missing-auth/endpoint gap."},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"COMMENT","timestamp":1782531398409804001,"uuid":"c86fd873-bb89-41bd-89de-da6de3ebebca"}